05025nmm a2200685Ia 9780520381964DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203819647 a10.1525/97805203819642doi  a(DE-B1597)642427  a(OCoLC)1374541259  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aK644b.S85 2023 7aLAW0430002bisacsh04a342.08/78223/eng/202212011 aSuk, Julie C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAfter Misogyny :bHow the Law Fails Women and What to Do about It /cJulie C. Suk. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Legal Patriarchy and Its Aftermath -- tPart I. How the Law Fails Women misogyny beyond misogynists -- t1 The Equal Protection of Feminists and Misogynists -- t2 Overentitlement and Overempowerment -- t3. Misogyny and Maternity: Abortion Bans as Overentitlement -- tPart II. What to Do about It remaking constitutions and democracy -- t4. From Patriarchy to Prohibition: Resetting Entitlements through Constitutional Change -- t5 Rebalancing Power through Parity Democracy -- t6. Building Feminist Infrastructures: The Constitutionalism of Care -- tConclusion: Toward a Feminist Remaking of Constitutional Democracy -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA rigorous analysis of systemic misogyny in the law and a thoughtful exploration of the tools needed to transcend it through constitutional change beyond litigation in the courts. Just as racism is embedded in the legal system, so is misogyny—even after the law proclaims gender equality and criminally punishes violence against women. In After Misogyny, Julie C. Suk shows that misogyny lies not in animus but in the overempowerment of men and the overentitlement of society to women's unpaid labor and undervalued contributions. This is a book about misogyny without misogynists. From antidiscrimination law to abortion bans, the law fails women by keeping society's dependence on women's sacrifices invisible. Via a tour of constitutional change around the world, After Misogyny shows how to remake constitutional democracy. Women across the globe are going beyond the antidiscrimination paradigm of American legal feminism and fundamentally resetting baseline norms and entitlements. That process, what Suk calls a ";constitutionalism of care,"; builds the public infrastructure that women's reproductive work has long made possible for free.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminist jurisprudence. 0aJustice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aSex discrimination against womenzUnited States. 0aSex discrimination against women. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etcxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etcxSocial aspects. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.xSocial aspects. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023 Englishz978311131914808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023z9783111318226oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520381964?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520381964423Coveruhtt